[{"id":38963,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"We know\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{r}=0.529 \\frac{\\mathrm{n}^2}{\\mathrm{Z}} \\Rightarrow 8.48=0.529 \\frac{\\mathrm{n}^2}{1} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{n}^2=16 \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{n}=4\n\\end{aligned}$<br />We know\n$\\mathrm{E} \\propto \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}^2}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& E_{n^{\\text {th }}}=\\frac{E}{16} \\\\\n& x=16\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38954,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["(A) is false but (R) is true","(A) is true but (R) is false","Both \\((\\mathbf{A})\\) and \\((\\mathbf{R})\\) are true and \\((\\mathbf{R})\\) is the correct explanation of \\((\\mathbf{A})\\)","Both \\((\\mathbf{A})\\) and \\((\\mathbf{R})\\) are true but \\((\\mathbf{R})\\) is not the correct explanation of \\((\\mathbf{A})\\)"],"answer":3,"solution":"Assertion (A) is true because a sufficiently negative potential can repel and stop the emitted electrons from leaving the surface.\r\nReason (R) is also true because the stopping potential \\(V_{\\text {stop }}\\) varies linearly with the frequency \\(\\nu\\) of the incident light \\(\\left(V_{\\text {stop }}=\\frac{h}{e} \\nu-\\frac{\\phi}{e}\\right)\\).\r\nHowever, (R) does not directly explain why a negative potential suppresses electron emission; it only shows how much potential is needed for different frequencies.\r\nTherefore, both (A) and (R) are true, but (R) is not the correct explanation of (A).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38959,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} v & =\\sqrt{\\frac{4 \\mathrm{KZe}^2}{\\mathrm{mr}_{\\text {min }}}} \\\\ & =\\sqrt{\\frac{4 \\times 9 \\times 10^9 \\times 80}{6.72 \\times 10^{-27} \\times 4.5 \\times 10^{-14}}} \\times 1.6 \\times 10^{-19} \\\\ & =9.759 \\times 10^{25} \\times 1.6 \\times 10^{-19} \\\\ & =156 \\times 10^5 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38976,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["Both statement I and statement II are false","Statement I is false but statement II is true","Statement I is true but statement II is false","Both statement I and statement II are true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rutherford proposed that most of the mass of an atom is concentrated in a small, dense nucleus at the centre, which contains positively charged protons. Electrons, carrying negative charge, revolve around the nucleus in orbits.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the Bohr model, electrons do not move in random orbits but have specific energy levels or shells around the nucleus. The electrons are not in a \"spherical cloud\" but are found in discrete orbits at fixed distances from the nucleus. Rutherford's model, on the other hand, did not specify the fixed orbits of electrons and was later refined by Bohr to explain the stability of atoms.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hence, statement I is true but statement II is false.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39039,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>27</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>144</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>36</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/><math><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>36</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>144</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39034,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>Rhc</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>c</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>c</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>c</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>C</mi></mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39018,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>57</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>46</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>44</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>38</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>As we know,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#957;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2.92</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup></mrow><mi>&#957;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#957;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2.92</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#957;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2.46</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39007,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>According to Bohr&#39;s postulates, angular momentum of an electron in an orbit is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Therefore, linear momentum&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39000,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#160;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#160;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#160;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mi>_</mi><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#160;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p>The wavelength of the light released when an&nbsp;electron&nbsp;jumps from higher energy state&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced></math>&nbsp;to lower energy state&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfenced></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>1</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mstyle></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>, here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi></math>&nbsp;is wavelength,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math>&nbsp;is Rydberg Constant.&nbsp;</p><p>When transition is from second excited state to&nbsp;first excited state,&nbsp;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn mathvariant=\"italic\">0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>When transition is from third excited state to&nbsp;second orbit</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mfenced><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mi>x</mi></mfrac></mstyle><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Dividing&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>by</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mn>20</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>36</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>27</mn><mn>20</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38938,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A, B Only","B, E Only","C, D Only","A, C, E Only"],"answer":3,"solution":"In Rutherford's alpha-particle scattering experiment, the rebounding of alpha particles (scattering angle $\\approx 180^{\\circ}$) occurs when they undergo a head-on collision with the gold nucleus.<br><br>A head-on collision corresponds to an impact parameter close to zero. Since the size of the gold nucleus ($\\approx 10^{-15}$ m) is extremely small compared to the size of the gold atom ($\\approx 10^{-10}$ m), the effective target area is very small. Consequently, the probability of an alpha particle having a minimum impact parameter is very low.<br><br>Thus, only a few alpha particles undergo head-on collisions and rebound back. This makes statements A, C, and E correct.<br><br>Statement B is incorrect because the charge of an alpha particle is $+2e$ while the charge of a gold nucleus is $+79e$.<br><br>Statement D is incorrect because the alpha particles emitted from the radioactive source have nearly the same kinetic energy.<br><br>Answer: A, C, E Only","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38977,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For minimum potential difference, electron has to make transition from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>  state but first electron has to reach to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math> state from ground state. So, energy of bombarding electron should be equal to energy difference of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> state.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Δ</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>V</mi></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>09</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>≈</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">So, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>121</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39071,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <mo>/</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <mo>&#916;</mo> <mtext>E</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>h</mtext> <mi>&#957;</mi> </mrow> </math><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>&#957;</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mo>&#916;</mo> <mtext>E</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>h</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>k</mtext> <mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>-</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfenced> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>k</mtext> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>n</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> <msup> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>&#8776;</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>k</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&#8733;</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":38988,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["Zero","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Bohr&#39;s formula for angular momentum&nbsp;of an electron in an orbit&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>For the first orbit,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;and the angular momentum is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>h</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi></math></p><p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>nd</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;orbit</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi></math></p><p>Hence, the change in angular momentum is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38980,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>16</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>From Bohr's atomic model, it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>Z</mi></mfrac><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Following equation (1), it can be written that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>16</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39024,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>U</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>U</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>r</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>U</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>n</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39054,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><msubsup><mrow><mo>∧</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>≈</mo><mi>λ</mi></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mo>∧</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≈</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mo>∧</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≈</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msubsup><mrow><mo>∧</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>≈</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>B</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><msub><mrow><mo>&#8907;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mo>&#8907;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&#8907;</mo><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>o</mi></msub><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>o</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&#8743;&#8203;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced close=\"}\" open=\"{\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mo>&#8743;&#8203;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close=\"}\" open=\"{\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mo>&#8743;&#8203;</mo><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mfenced open=\"{\" close=\"}\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math><br /><br />from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mo>&#8743;&#8203;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced close=\"}\" open=\"{\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msubsup><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mo>&#8907;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mo>&#8907;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39063,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["(I)-(A), (II)-(B), (III)-(B),,(IV)-(C)","(I)-(A), (II)-(B), (III)-(C), (IV)-(C)","(I)-(D), (II)-(C), (III)-(A), (IV)-(B)","(I)-(B), (II)-(A), (III)-(D), (IV)-(A)"],"answer":3,"solution":"Wavelength emitted by atomic hydrogen in interstellar space - Part of short radio wave of electromagnetic spectrum. Doublet of sodium - visible radiation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39050,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["(A), (B), (D)","(B), (D)","(C),(D)","(A), (C), (D)"],"answer":3,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&\\text { (A) Radius of muon }=\\frac{\\text { Radius of hydrogen }}{200} \\\\\n&\\text { Radius of } \\mathrm{H} \\text { atom }=r=\\frac{\\in_0 n^2 h^2}{\\pi m e^2} \\\\\n&\\text { Radius of muon }=r_\\mu=\\frac{\\in_0 n^2 h^2}{\\pi \\times 200 m e^2} \\\\\n&r_\\mu=\\frac{r}{200}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n(B) Velocity relation given is wrong\n(C) Ionization energy in $e^{-} \\mathrm{H}$ atom\n$$\nE=\\frac{+m e^4}{8 \\epsilon_0^2 n^2 h^2}\n$$\n\n$$\nE_\\mu=\\frac{200 m e^4}{8 \\epsilon_0^2 n^2 h^2}=200 E\n$$\n(D) Momentum of $\\mathrm{H}$-atom\n$$\nm v r=\\frac{n h}{2 \\pi}\n$$\nHence (A), (C), (D) are correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":38971,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Energy liberated is given by, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>∆</mo><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>×</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3600</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>kW</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3600</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3600</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi>kW</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>kW</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38991,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula to calculate the radius of Lithium-ion is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>Li</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>Z</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Substitute the values of the known parameters into equation (1) to calculate the required radius of the ion.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>51</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>425</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38945,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$3.85 \\times 10^{-16}$","$3.85 \\times 10^{-14}$","$2.95 \\times 10^{-16}$","$2.95 \\times 10^{-14}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"At closest approach, KE converts to PE:<br>$KE = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0} \\times \\frac{(2e)(Ze)}{r_{min}}$<br>$r_{min} = \\frac{9 \\times 10^9 \\times 2 \\times 79 \\times (1.6 \\times 10^{-19})^2}{7.7 \\times 10^6 \\times 1.6 \\times 10^{-19}}$<br>$= \\frac{9 \\times 2 \\times 79 \\times 1.6 \\times 10^{-19}}{7.7} \\times 10^{3}$<br>$= \\frac{2275.2}{7.7} \\times 10^{-16} = 2.95 \\times 10^{-14}$ m","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39081,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$2 \\rightarrow 1$","$3 \\rightarrow 2$","$4 \\rightarrow 2$","$5 \\rightarrow 4$"],"answer":3,"solution":"IR corresponds to least value of $\\left(\\frac{1}{n_1^2}-\\frac{1}{n_2^2}\\right)$\ni.e. from Paschen, Bracket and Pfund series. Thus the transition corresponds to $5 \\rightarrow 3$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":39080,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$36.3 \\mathrm{eV}$","$108.8 \\mathrm{eV}$","$122.4 \\mathrm{eV}$","$12.1 \\mathrm{eV}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$E_n=-13.6 \\frac{Z^2}{n^2}$\n$E_{\\mathrm{L}}{ }^{* *}=-13.6 \\times \\frac{9}{1}=-122.4 \\mathrm{eV}$\n$E_{\\mathrm{L}}{ }^{* *}=-13.6 \\times \\frac{9}{9}=-13.6 \\mathrm{eV}$\n$\\Delta E=-13.6-(-122.4)$\n$=108.8 \\mathrm{eV}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":39006,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Energy of a photon released in transition of electron in hydrogen atom is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8734;</mo></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mi>x</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39043,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>889.2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>488.9</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>388.9</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math> <mrow>  <mn>642.7</mn><mtext>&#x2009;</mtext><mtext>nm</mtext></mrow></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"From Rydberg’s equation, <br/><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>  <br/><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>660</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>  <br/><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>  <br/><math><mfrac><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>600</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>16</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/><math><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>488.9</mn><mtext> </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39032,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["The ionization potential of hydrogen, second member of Balmer series and third member of Paschen series.","The series limit of Lyman series, second member of Balmer series and second member of Paschen series.","The series limit of Lyman series, third member of Balmer series and second member of Paschen series.","The first member of the Lyman series, third member of Balmer series and second member of Paschen series."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>&nbsp;Series limit of Lyman series.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>&nbsp;Third member of Balmer series.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>&nbsp;Second member of Paschen series.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39085,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["III","IV","I","II"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\Delta \\mathrm{E} \\propto\\left(\\frac{1}{n_1^2}-\\frac{1}{n_2^2}\\right)$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":39078,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$2$","$3$","$5$","$6$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Number of spectral lines from a state $\\mathrm{n}$ to ground state is\n$=\\frac{n(n-1)}{2}=6.$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":39038,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>1.6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>7.8</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>6.2</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>5.6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math><mi>T</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi></mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math></p><p>now,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;<br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12.8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>7.8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38973,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Magnetic moment of electron is given by, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>h</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msub><mi>m</mi><mi>e</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Clearly, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>∝</mo><mo> </mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math>. Therefore, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39079,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\left(m_1+m_2\\right)^2 n^2 h^2}{2 m_1^2 m_2^2 r^2}$","$\\frac{n^2 h^2}{2\\left(m_1+m_2\\right) r^2}$","$\\frac{2 n^2 h^2}{\\left(m_1+m_2\\right) r^2}$","$\\frac{\\left(m_1+m_2\\right) n^2 h^2}{2 m_1 m_2 r^2}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$r_1=\\frac{m_2 r}{m_1+m_2} ; r_2=\\frac{m_1 r}{m_1+m_2}$\n$\\left(l_1+l_2\\right) \\omega=\\frac{n h}{2 \\pi}=nh$\n$K . E=\\frac{1}{2}\\left(l_1+l_2\\right) \\omega^2=\\frac{n^2 h^2\\left(m_1+m_2\\right)}{2 m_1 m_2 r^2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":39074,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$207 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$465 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$310 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$620 \\mathrm{~nm}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$E=\\frac{h c}{\\lambda}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":38953,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["3","1","6","0"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1Ok4KO6n-xe31beKyB30hegBguK1yUj_C4_LJz6pQJA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39060,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Let us assume that the electron in the&nbsp;lithium-ion is knocked off from the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mi>th</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;energy level, then</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><msup><mfenced><msub><mi>Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfrac><msup><mfenced><msub><mi>Z</mi><mi>Li</mi></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><msup><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mfenced><mn>3</mn></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>12</mn></msqrt><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p>Hence the least quantum number must be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39008,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The relation&nbsp;between impact parameter and scattering angle is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi>z</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>E</mi></mfrac><mi>cot</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>cot</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msqrt><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msqrt><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>cot</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msqrt><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>cot</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>90</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msqrt><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msqrt><msqrt><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>cot</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>cot</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>90</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null}]